; preludes: form-stdlib/core.fk form-stdlib/nearest-shape.fk form-stdlib/co-learning.fk
;
; co-learning-band — two mics learn faster together, proven three-way.
;
; Device A (Mac mic) heard SPEECH; device B (Android mic) heard MUSIC. Each learned only its own shape:
;   A = [ ("speech", [5 0 0]) ]        B = [ ("music", [0 5 0]) ]
; A's classifier is partial — shown a MUSIC feature it has no music exemplar, so nearest-shape routes it
; to its only prototype (speech): WRONG. B is partial the other way. The mesh-merge (the union of what
; both mics taught) recognizes BOTH — the federated speedup: two streams cover what one cannot.
;
; Verdict 127 when every claim lands:
;   1   A alone gets MUSIC wrong         (cl-knows? music A "music" == 0 — A never heard music)
;   2   B alone gets SPEECH wrong        (cl-knows? speech B "speech" == 0)
;   4   the MERGE gets speech right       (cl-knows? speech A∪B "speech" == 1)
;   8   the MERGE gets music right        (cl-knows? music  A∪B "music"  == 1)
;   16  each cell is still right on its OWN shape   (A knows speech)
;   32  ... and B knows music                       (sanity: the union didn't lose either)
;   64  the union carries both exemplars            (cl-breadth A∪B == 2)
(do
    (let speech (list 5 0 0))
    (let music  (list 0 5 0))
    (let a (list (list "speech" speech)))
    (let b (list (list "music" music)))
    (let m (cl-merge a b))
    (let c0 (if (eq (cl-knows? music  a "music")  0) 1 0))
    (let c1 (if (eq (cl-knows? speech b "speech") 0) 2 0))
    (let c2 (if (eq (cl-knows? speech m "speech") 1) 4 0))
    (let c3 (if (eq (cl-knows? music  m "music")  1) 8 0))
    (let c4 (if (eq (cl-knows? speech a "speech") 1) 16 0))
    (let c5 (if (eq (cl-knows? music  b "music")  1) 32 0))
    (let c6 (if (eq (cl-breadth m) 2) 64 0))
    (add c0 (add c1 (add c2 (add c3 (add c4 (add c5 c6)))))))
